00:00:21.590 --> 00:00:25.230
PROFESSOR: Our goal for
today is to basically analyze

00:00:25.230 --> 00:00:27.530
this simple model to death.

00:00:27.530 --> 00:00:30.520
So we're first going
to try to understand

00:00:30.520 --> 00:00:34.190
the deterministic behavior
of this model gene

00:00:34.190 --> 00:00:38.130
expression, where we just
get transcription of mRNA,

00:00:38.130 --> 00:00:40.100
and then translation of protein.

00:00:40.100 --> 00:00:43.272
And after we think we
understand the mean behavior,

00:00:43.272 --> 00:00:44.730
the deterministic
dynamics, then we

00:00:44.730 --> 00:00:48.490
will try to understand
just stochastic behavior

00:00:48.490 --> 00:00:49.400
in this model.

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:51.370
So we're going to
try to understand

00:00:51.370 --> 00:00:55.450
what's the distribution
of mRNA in a cell

00:00:55.450 --> 00:00:56.920
in this simple situation.

00:00:56.920 --> 00:00:58.770
What's the distribution
of protein?

00:00:58.770 --> 00:01:01.400
What's going to be
the bursting behavior?

00:01:01.400 --> 00:01:02.900
Everything you can
possibly think of

00:01:02.900 --> 00:01:05.070
to ask about this
model, we will hopefully

00:01:05.070 --> 00:01:08.230
have asked by the
end of today's class.

00:01:08.230 --> 00:01:10.150
This simple model
of gene expression,

00:01:10.150 --> 00:01:12.830
as was indicated in
the review, is perhaps

00:01:12.830 --> 00:01:15.800
a reasonable description
of gene expression

00:01:15.800 --> 00:01:21.180
in bacteria, when the gene
is in some active state.

00:01:21.180 --> 00:01:25.312
So there's no repressor,
for example, bound.

00:01:25.312 --> 00:01:26.770
Although maybe even
in the presence

00:01:26.770 --> 00:01:28.660
of a repressor, if it's
binding and unbinding,

00:01:28.660 --> 00:01:31.118
maybe you still end up getting
some sort of renormalization

00:01:31.118 --> 00:01:32.600
that looks like this.

00:01:32.600 --> 00:01:35.220
But this is first order,
a reasonable description

00:01:35.220 --> 00:01:38.710
of gene expression in bacteria.

00:01:38.710 --> 00:01:41.460
And it's the model
that was basically

00:01:41.460 --> 00:01:44.070
used in the Sunney Xie
paper that we talked about

00:01:44.070 --> 00:01:44.860
on Tuesday.

00:01:44.860 --> 00:01:46.560
And hopefully this
model will allow

00:01:46.560 --> 00:01:49.880
us to think a little bit
more deeply about the data

00:01:49.880 --> 00:01:53.640
that they obtained
in that paper.

00:01:53.640 --> 00:01:57.320
As always, we want to
start by understanding

00:01:57.320 --> 00:01:58.612
the basic aspects of the model.

00:01:58.612 --> 00:02:00.070
So what we're going
to do, is we're

00:02:00.070 --> 00:02:02.010
going to go through
a series of questions

00:02:02.010 --> 00:02:03.660
of increasing difficulty.

00:02:03.660 --> 00:02:06.580
And in some of
them, we are indeed,

00:02:06.580 --> 00:02:12.242
the answers will end up being
something divided by something.

00:02:12.242 --> 00:02:14.200
In which case you take
advantage of your cards,

