00:06:35.430 --> 00:06:40.810
So mRNA are actively
degraded, typically.

00:06:40.810 --> 00:06:44.117
They're also just kind of
less stable intrinsically.

00:06:44.117 --> 00:06:45.700
But what we're going
to assume for now

00:06:45.700 --> 00:06:48.890
is that we're working
with stable proteins.

00:06:48.890 --> 00:06:54.340
In which case the growth
rate of the population

00:06:54.340 --> 00:06:57.270
will just be this
effective degradation

00:06:57.270 --> 00:06:59.450
rate of the protein.

00:06:59.450 --> 00:07:01.420
So in this model,
even if we say there's

00:07:01.420 --> 00:07:04.050
no active degradation
of the protein,

00:07:04.050 --> 00:07:08.940
still there's going to be some
effective degradation that's

00:07:08.940 --> 00:07:10.930
due to dilution.

00:07:10.930 --> 00:07:13.308
So we can say
effective, if you like.

00:07:16.280 --> 00:07:18.819
So the rate of exponential
growth of the population

00:07:18.819 --> 00:07:20.610
will be equal to this
effective degradation

00:07:20.610 --> 00:07:22.151
rate for the protein,
if it's stable.

00:07:24.590 --> 00:07:26.590
AUDIENCE: So you're talking
about the population

00:07:26.590 --> 00:07:28.990
of the protein?

00:07:28.990 --> 00:07:30.000
PROFESSOR: No.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:33.240
The growth rate of
the cell population.

00:07:33.240 --> 00:07:37.620
So this is if we go
in there, and you

00:07:37.620 --> 00:07:38.980
go into your spectrophotometer.

00:07:38.980 --> 00:07:42.190
And you measure population--
numbers in function of time

00:07:42.190 --> 00:07:43.280
is growing exponentially.

00:07:43.280 --> 00:07:45.300
It'll grow exponentially
with this rate.

00:07:45.300 --> 00:07:47.710
Because this is what's
causing the dilution.

00:07:47.710 --> 00:07:52.423
In some ways if you
stop making the protein,

00:07:52.423 --> 00:07:54.506
and you double the number
of cells, and that means

00:07:54.506 --> 00:07:57.100
the concentration of
the protein in each cell

00:07:57.100 --> 00:07:59.420
has to go down by
a factor of two.

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:00.420
So that's the statement.

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:05.347
Are there any questions about
why I'm making this argument?

00:08:05.347 --> 00:08:05.846
Yes?

00:08:05.846 --> 00:08:08.280
AUDIENCE: What was the relevance
of the protein being stable?

00:08:08.280 --> 00:08:08.720
PROFESSOR: All right.

00:08:08.720 --> 00:08:10.261
So the relevance of
the protein being

00:08:10.261 --> 00:08:14.700
stable, because this is in
general, this delta, this

00:08:14.700 --> 00:08:17.540
is the effective rate.

00:08:17.540 --> 00:08:20.970
This is going to be equal to the
growth rate of the population.

00:08:20.970 --> 00:08:25.740
So you might call
it gamma growth

00:08:25.740 --> 00:08:30.010
plus the actual degradation.

00:08:30.010 --> 00:08:32.599
I don't want to use
the same, but I'll just

00:08:32.599 --> 00:08:34.770
say plus the degradation rate.

00:08:34.770 --> 00:08:40.627
And this is a true physical
degradation, true degradation

00:08:40.627 --> 00:08:42.750
rate of the protein.

00:08:42.750 --> 00:08:47.380
So if it's stable, then we
say that this thing is zero.

00:08:47.380 --> 00:08:48.820
So when we say
stable protein, it

00:08:48.820 --> 00:08:50.970
means there's no
degradation of the protein.

00:08:50.970 --> 00:08:53.700
So this physical
degradation rate is zero.

00:08:53.700 --> 00:08:56.070
And then the effective
degradation rate of the protein

00:08:56.070 --> 00:08:59.148
is just equal to the growth
rate of the population.

00:08:59.148 --> 00:09:02.052
AUDIENCE: OK, so no degradation
means stable, basically?

00:09:02.052 --> 00:09:05.434
PROFESSOR: Yes, sorry, yeah.

00:09:05.434 --> 00:09:07.350
