these situations

00:30:16.980 --> 00:30:25.185
to define some probability
rho, which is the probability

00:30:25.185 --> 00:30:27.360
you actually, if
you're here, it's

00:30:27.360 --> 00:30:32.110
the probability that you
produce one protein at least.

00:30:32.110 --> 00:30:34.930
The question is, which
path do you take initially.

00:30:34.930 --> 00:30:36.620
Well that's just
given by the ratios.

00:30:36.620 --> 00:30:39.980
So there's the rate that we
take this circular path divided

00:30:39.980 --> 00:30:42.120
by the sum of these
two other rates.

00:30:47.320 --> 00:30:49.710
And then what we can
do is we can ask, well

00:30:49.710 --> 00:30:55.570
what is the probability that
0 proteins are produced,

00:30:55.570 --> 00:30:58.420
probability that we get 0.

00:30:58.420 --> 00:31:02.700
Well if we take
this path initially,

00:31:02.700 --> 00:31:04.019
will we have 0 proteins?

00:31:04.019 --> 00:31:04.560
AUDIENCE: No.

00:31:04.560 --> 00:31:05.150
PROFESSOR: No.

00:31:05.150 --> 00:31:08.110
Right, so this
probability is indeed

00:31:08.110 --> 00:31:12.010
simply equal to the probability
that we do this first, which

00:31:12.010 --> 00:31:13.560
is 1 minus rho.

00:31:20.394 --> 00:31:22.310
Now what's the probably
that we get 1 protein?

00:31:22.310 --> 00:31:24.640
Well, only 1?

00:31:24.640 --> 00:31:28.740
That's equal to the probability
that we first take this path,

00:31:28.740 --> 00:31:30.682
and then we take this path.

00:31:30.682 --> 00:31:32.390
Well we can multiply
those probabilities.

00:31:32.390 --> 00:31:35.350
Because we first take
the circular path

00:31:35.350 --> 00:31:36.770
to make a protein.

00:31:36.770 --> 00:31:39.920
And then we take the
degradation path.

00:31:39.920 --> 00:31:41.690
Well what's the
probability we get 2?

00:31:41.690 --> 00:31:44.110
Well that's just that we
come around here once,

00:31:44.110 --> 00:31:45.450
twice, and then degrade.

00:31:50.540 --> 00:31:52.830
Now if you're not
seeing a pattern here,

00:31:52.830 --> 00:31:54.840
then we're in trouble.

00:31:57.400 --> 00:31:58.910
So this says the
probability of n

00:31:58.910 --> 00:32:02.730
will then just be equal to
rho to the n, 1 minus rho.

00:32:08.850 --> 00:32:11.340
And indeed, it's
always useful in order

00:32:11.340 --> 00:32:13.370
to warm up your
probability muscles,

00:32:13.370 --> 00:32:17.880
to check to make sure that this
is a normalized probability

00:32:17.880 --> 00:32:18.830
distribution.

00:32:18.830 --> 00:32:25.820
So sum over all possible
ends indeed goes to 1.

00:32:25.820 --> 00:32:29.190
And that's just because the sum
over a bunch of rho to the n's

00:32:29.190 --> 00:32:32.440
is equal to 1 divided by 1 minus
rho, which is the term there.

00:32:32.440 --> 00:32:34.591
And that goes to 1.

00:32:34.591 --> 00:32:37.682
AUDIENCE: So this is making
a pretty strong assumption

00:32:37.682 --> 00:32:38.890
that they're all independent?

00:32:38.890 --> 00:32:41.180
PROFESSOR: Yep, yep.

00:32:41.180 --> 00:32:42.540
Yep.

00:32:42.540 --> 00:32:47.970
This is assuming that if you've
gone around once, you return.

00:32:47.970 --> 00:32:50.100
But I've come back to
the original state.

00:32:50.100 --> 00:32:51.962
AUDIENCE: But do
mRNAs like actually

00:32:51.962 --> 00:32:55.060
get caught in ribosomes--

00:32:55.060 --> 00:32:58.720
PROFESSOR: There are a lot
of things that can be true.

00:32:58.720 --> 00:33:03.972
And I would say that
in biology and in life,

00:33:03.972 --> 00:33:05.430
what you do is you
first write down

00:33:05.430 --> 00:33:06.790
the simplest possible model.

00:33:06.790 --> 00:33:08.540
And then you go and
you make measurements.

00:33:08.540 --> 00:33:12.300
And you ask whether the simplest
possible model can adequately

00:33:12.300 --> 00:33:13.380
explain the data.

00:33:13.380 --> 00:33:15.086
And if the answer
is no, then you're

00:33:15.086 --> 00:33:16.960
allowed to start thinking
about other things.

00:33:16.960 --> 00:33:19.770
Because everything's
is in principle true.

00:33:19.770 --> 00:33:22.400
In that mRNA, maybe
it's this or that.

00:33:22.400 --> 00:33:24.130
The question is whether
it's significant.

00:33:24.130 --> 00:33:26.046
And at least from the
data from Sunney's group

00:33:26.046 --> 00:33:29.807
would say that in that
condition, in those cells,

00:33:29.807 --> 00:33:31.390
that those things
are not significant,

00:33:31.390 --> 00:33:33.950
in the sense that you still
get a geometric distribution.

00:33:33.950 --> 00:33:37.429
Of course it could also be that
those other things actually are

00:33:37.429 --> 00:33:38.470
true and are significant.

00:33:38.470 --> 00:33:41.120
But then you end up
with some new parameters

00:33:41.120 --> 00:33:45.260
that describe how things look as
a result of all the complexity.

00:33:45.260 --> 00:33:48.762
That's also OK in
the sense that I'd

00:33:48.762 --> 00:33:50.720
say that you can get a
quantitative description

00:33:50.720 --> 00:33:53.300
of the process by describing
it as a geometric with just

00:33:53.300 --> 00:33:54.580
a single free parameter.

00:33:54.580 --> 00:33:58.750
And they found that the mean
was four, or four or five.

00:33:58.750 --> 00:34:01.960
The mean number of proteins
produced from each mRNA.

00:34:01.960 --> 00:34:06.040
But they got this geometric
distribution in that paper.

00:34:10.809 --> 00:34:11.309
Yes?

00:34:15.159 --> 00:34:19.940
And I'll just mention
here that the mean of this

00:34:19.940 --> 00:34:21.730
is rho divided by 1 minus rho.

00:34:24.280 --> 00:34:26.860
So what you see is
that as rho goes to 1,

00:34:26.860 --> 00:34:29.060
then this thing is
going to diverge.

00:34:29.060 --> 00:34:30.050
And that makes sense.

00:34:30.050 --> 00:34:33.540
because as rho goes to 1, it's
saying that you essentially

00:34:33.540 --> 00:34:37.750
always synthesize another
protein rather than degrading.

00:34:37.750 --> 00:34:39.520
And before I move
on, I just want

00:34:39.520 --> 00:34:41.270
to say one more thing,
which is that there

00:34:41.270 --> 00:34:44.507
are many different definitions
of the geometric distribution,

00:34:44.507 --> 00:34:46.382
depending upon whether
the probability of rho

00:34:46.382 --> 00:34:47.390
is the probability
of terminating,

00:34:47.390 --> 00:34:49.640
or the probability of going
around, and also depending

00:34:49.640 --> 00:34:52.300
on whether you're asking
what is the-- here

00:34:52.300 --> 00:34:53.860
we're talking about
the probability

00:34:53.860 --> 00:34:56.320
distribution for the number
of proteins produced.

00:34:56.320 --> 00:34:57.690
Whereas we could have
talked about the probability

00:34:57.690 --> 00:35:00.148
distribution for the number of
times we go around this loop

00:35:00.148 --> 00:35:03.150
before, no, no sorry.

00:35:03.150 --> 00:35:05.200
That is for the number
of proteins produced.

00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:09.000
So the other way you could
have defined this is the number

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:14.960
of times where it's-- the number
of cycles that you had to go

00:35:14.960 --> 00:35:17.360
before you went here, in the
sense that if you first go

00:35:17.360 --> 00:35:19.756
here, you can either
call that a 0 or a 1.

00:35:19.756 --> 00:35:20.880
Do you see what I'm saying?

00:35:20.880 --> 00:35:22.890
And reasonable
people can disagree.

00:35:22.890 --> 00:35:25.570
But you end up getting
distributions that are

00:35:25.570 --> 00:35:27.200
just a little bit different.

00:35:27.200 --> 00:35:28.250
So watch out.

00:35:28.250 --> 00:35:30.060
If you just memorize
something, you

00:35:30.060 --> 00:35:32.050
might have memorized
the equation

00:35:32.050 --> 00:35:35.240
for a different definition
of this distribution.

00:35:35.240 --> 00:35:38.780
Does everyone understand
what I tried to say there?

00:35:38.780 --> 00:35:39.380
Maybe?

00:35:39.380 --> 00:35:40.285
Yeah?

00:35:40.285 --> 00:35:41.826
AUDIENCE: When
there's no degradation

00:35:41.826 --> 00:35:43.492
is it still a Poisson?

00:35:43.492 --> 00:35:46.550
PROFESSOR: Ah, if there's no
degradation then would this

00:35:46.550 --> 00:35:48.040
be a Poisson?

00:35:48.040 --> 00:35:52.329
I mean, this would
be infinity, right?

00:35:52.329 --> 00:35:53.870
AUDIENCE: Right,
[INAUDIBLE] protein,

00:35:53.870 --> 00:35:57.216
this is done independently,
like there's an mRNA.

00:35:57.216 --> 00:35:59.620
[INAUDIBLE] proteins
independently.

00:35:59.620 --> 00:36:01.654
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:36:01.654 --> 00:36:02.570
So I want to be clear.

00:36:02.570 --> 00:36:08.000
This is, p of n is,
this is the probability

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:18.150
distribution for
number of proteins n,

00:36:18.150 --> 00:36:19.480
produced from a single mRNA.

00:36:26.020 --> 00:36:30.059
Now if there's no
degradation of the mRNA,

00:36:30.059 --> 00:36:31.600
then this thing is
not even, I think,

00:36:31.600 --> 00:36:35.940
defined in that the
number of proteins

00:36:35.940 --> 00:36:39.330
produced from that mRNA just
really goes to infinity.

00:36:39.330 --> 00:36:43.090
If you wanted to ask about
the probability distribution

00:36:43.090 --> 00:36:45.170
for the number of
proteins produced

00:36:45.170 --> 00:36:49.470
in some unit, some period
of time that would indeed

00:36:49.470 --> 00:36:53.410
be a Poisson
distribution, assuming

00:36:53.410 --> 00:36:56.210
that there's no degradation.

00:36:56.210 --> 00:36:58.972
Do you understand what
I'm trying to say?

00:36:58.972 --> 00:37:02.780
AUDIENCE: So Sp is like 0?

00:37:02.780 --> 00:37:06.330
PROFESSOR: If Sp, I'm sorry.

00:37:06.330 --> 00:37:07.872
If Sp were 0?

00:37:07.872 --> 00:37:09.038
AUDIENCE: Yeah. [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:21.367 --> 00:37:21.950
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:37:21.950 --> 00:37:24.325
And you're saying that what
would be Poisson distributed?

00:37:24.325 --> 00:37:26.225
AUDIENCE: The
number of proteins.

00:37:36.090 --> 00:37:38.430
PROFESSOR: Yeah, I think
that actually-- no I

00:37:38.430 --> 00:37:41.940
think that-- I think that
you're probably right.

00:37:41.940 --> 00:37:45.176
That as Sp goes to 0-- I'm
a little bit worried that--

00:37:45.176 --> 00:37:46.050
AUDIENCE: No, no, no.

00:37:46.050 --> 00:37:46.670
Zero-th order, sorry.

00:37:46.670 --> 00:37:47.436
PROFESSOR: Oh.

00:37:47.436 --> 00:37:49.284
AUDIENCE: Not 0.

00:37:49.284 --> 00:37:52.220
[INAUDIBLE]

00:37:52.220 --> 00:37:53.135
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:37:53.135 --> 00:37:55.260
Right, so the mRNA distribution
we're about to find

00:37:55.260 --> 00:37:58.250
is indeed going to be a
Poisson at steady state.

00:37:58.250 --> 00:38:01.090
And so if there's some
process by which the protein

00:38:01.090 --> 00:38:02.980
distribution is
really just mirroring

00:38:02.980 --> 00:38:07.810
the mRNA distribution, then
it will also be Poisson.

00:38:07.810 --> 00:38:10.680
Although I think you have to be
careful about how you actually

00:38:10.680 --> 00:38:12.050
implement that.

00:38:12.050 --> 00:38:15.290
Because even in the absence
of this geometric bursting,

00:38:15.290 --> 00:38:17.390
different things, I
think, can happen.

00:38:17.390 --> 00:38:20.420
Because for example, if there
were exactly 10 proteins

00:38:20.420 --> 00:38:23.800
produced from each mRNA, then
that probability distribution

00:38:23.800 --> 00:38:26.240
is a shift.

00:38:26.240 --> 00:38:29.570
But then it's no
longer actually going

00:38:29.570 --> 00:38:33.150
to be Poisson, because the mean
and variance are going to scale

00:38:33.150 --> 00:38:35.450
differently if you do that.

00:38:35.450 --> 00:38:38.450
Let's maybe do the Poisson
distribution for the mRNA

00:38:38.450 --> 00:38:38.950
first.

00:38:38.950 --> 00:38:42.420
And then we can try
to touch back on this.

00:38:46.040 --> 00:38:49.790
So this is a plot of kind
of geometric distribution

00:38:49.790 --> 00:38:51.155
with a mean of 3-4-ish.

00:38:56.860 --> 00:39:00.312
Is everybody happy
with where we are now?

00:39:00.312 --> 00:39:02.060
OK.

00:39:02.060 --> 00:39:04.290
Now from this, what
we've said so far

00:39:04.290 --> 00:39:06.770
is it obvious what the
distribution of proteins

00:39:06.770 --> 00:39:08.580
will be in a cell?

00:39:08.580 --> 00:39:10.080
We can say obvious, yes.

00:39:10.080 --> 00:39:12.920
Or not obvious, no.

00:39:12.920 --> 00:39:15.330
Ready, just verbal, yes?

00:39:15.330 --> 00:39:16.020
Ready or no?

00:39:16.020 --> 00:39:16.520
All right.

00:39:16.520 --> 00:39:17.020
Ready?

00:39:17.020 --> 00:39:17.690
Three, two, one.

00:39:17.690 --> 00:39:18.317
AUDIENCE: No.

00:39:18.317 --> 00:39:18.900
PROFESSOR: No.

00:39:18.900 --> 00:39:19.570
Right.

00:39:19.570 --> 00:39:22.560
So we've said that
the distribution

00:39:22.560 --> 00:39:25.116
of size of protein bursts
from single mRNA is geometric.

00:39:25.116 --> 00:39:26.490
But that doesn't
mean that that's

00:39:26.490 --> 00:39:29.919
going to be the distribution
of proteins in the cell.

00:39:29.919 --> 00:39:31.460
And indeed after,
we're going to find

00:39:31.460 --> 00:39:33.790
that the distribution of
mRNA is going to be Poisson.

00:39:33.790 --> 00:39:35.830
But even then it's not
obvious what the distribution

00:39:35.830 --> 00:39:36.455
of proteins is.

00:39:47.410 --> 00:39:47.910
All right.

00:39:47.910 --> 00:39:49.410
So what we want to
do now is we want

00:39:49.410 --> 00:39:51.390
to introduce kind of a
simple version of what's

00:39:51.390 --> 00:39:52.650
known as the Master Equation.

00:39:55.390 --> 00:39:58.010
Now you guys are going to
do more reading on this

00:39:58.010 --> 00:40:00.330
for the lecture on Tuesday.

00:40:00.330 --> 00:40:03.080
Where we're going to talk about
the Master Equation, as well

00:40:03.080 --> 00:40:06.310
as the Fokker-Planck
approximation.

00:40:06.310 --> 00:40:08.620
Maybe the Gillespie
algorithm, and so forth.

00:40:08.620 --> 00:40:13.380
But I want to start by
thinking about the this notion

00:40:13.380 --> 00:40:15.084
in the simplest
possible context.

00:40:15.084 --> 00:40:16.500
So what we're going
to do is we're

00:40:16.500 --> 00:40:18.580
going to think about the world.

00:40:18.580 --> 00:40:21.550
So we want to know the steady
state, or the equilibrium

00:40:21.550 --> 00:40:26.170
distribution of mRNA numbers in
the cell, given this process.

00:40:26.170 --> 00:40:27.400
So that's great.

00:40:27.400 --> 00:40:31.630
We can-- so mRNA
distribution, question mark.

00:40:40.520 --> 00:40:43.520
Now in this case we don't
care about Sp, delta p,

00:40:43.520 --> 00:40:47.032
because the only things that are
relevant are going to be these.

00:40:47.032 --> 00:40:48.490
Now what we're
going to do is we're

00:40:48.490 --> 00:40:50.830
going to think about the
world in which we just

00:40:50.830 --> 00:40:54.010
defined states corresponding
to the different numbers

00:40:54.010 --> 00:40:54.950
of these mRNAs.

00:40:57.860 --> 00:41:01.170
So there's a state
where there's 0.

00:41:01.170 --> 00:41:03.120
We can't go to the
left, less than 0,

00:41:03.120 --> 00:41:09.490
but we can go to the state where
there's 1, or the state where

00:41:09.490 --> 00:41:10.620
there's 2, and so forth.

00:41:16.340 --> 00:41:18.590
Now the description
here is supposed

00:41:18.590 --> 00:41:21.680
to be the analog
of this over there.

00:41:21.680 --> 00:41:25.094
So this is trying to
understand the situation where

00:41:25.094 --> 00:41:27.010
the deterministic equations
would be described

00:41:27.010 --> 00:41:32.050
by m dot is equal to
this some synthesis rate,

00:41:32.050 --> 00:41:35.600
minus a degradation rate that's
proportional to the number,

00:41:35.600 --> 00:41:39.186
so minus delta m times m.

00:41:42.590 --> 00:41:46.880
So what you can see is that
the deterministic equations

00:41:46.880 --> 00:41:49.010
are very simple.

00:41:49.010 --> 00:41:51.296
We already calculated
the equilibrium.

00:41:51.296 --> 00:41:52.670
So when this thing
is equal to 0,

00:41:52.670 --> 00:41:55.185
then we get that m
equilibrium is just

00:41:55.185 --> 00:41:57.810
going to equal to the synthesis
rate divided by the degradation

00:41:57.810 --> 00:41:58.309
rate.

00:42:02.210 --> 00:42:03.830
If we're away from
the equilibrium

00:42:03.830 --> 00:42:05.836
in this deterministic
approximation,

00:42:05.836 --> 00:42:07.460
how long is it going
to take us to kind

00:42:07.460 --> 00:42:10.640
of approach our equilibrium?

00:42:10.640 --> 00:42:11.610
Verbal answer, ready?

00:42:11.610 --> 00:42:13.100
Three, two, one.

00:42:13.100 --> 00:42:14.192
[STUDENTS RESPOND]

00:42:14.192 --> 00:42:14.900
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:42:14.900 --> 00:42:17.130
So it's going to
be 1 over delta m.

00:42:17.130 --> 00:42:20.320
So this tells us the
characteristic timescale

00:42:20.320 --> 00:42:21.160
to come back.

00:42:21.160 --> 00:42:28.015
So if we're-- this is the
equilibrium Sm over delta m.

00:42:28.015 --> 00:42:31.570
This is m as a function of time.

00:42:31.570 --> 00:42:32.980
If we're below, we come here.

00:42:32.980 --> 00:42:35.070
If we're above, we come here.

00:42:35.070 --> 00:42:41.686
And this time is 1 over delta m.

00:42:41.686 --> 00:42:43.202
Are the any questions about?

00:42:50.920 --> 00:42:53.130
Now this-- so I
want to highlight

00:42:53.130 --> 00:42:58.640
that this is like the world's
simplest dynamical equation,

00:42:58.640 --> 00:43:01.654
almost the world's simplest.

00:43:01.654 --> 00:43:03.820
Yet what we're going to
find is that once we go over

00:43:03.820 --> 00:43:05.695
and we try to understand
the full probability

00:43:05.695 --> 00:43:08.320
distribution of the
stochastic system

00:43:08.320 --> 00:43:10.470
then it's a little
bit more complicated.

00:43:10.470 --> 00:43:13.140
In particular, we end
up with an infinite set

00:43:13.140 --> 00:43:15.710
of differential equations.

00:43:15.710 --> 00:43:18.640
So in general the
Master Equation format,

00:43:18.640 --> 00:43:21.380
where we're going to write
differential equations for how

00:43:21.380 --> 00:43:25.530
these probabilities
change over time.

00:43:25.530 --> 00:43:28.350
Now what we've done is we've
traded a single differential

00:43:28.350 --> 00:43:31.170
equation for an infinite number
of differential equations.

00:43:31.170 --> 00:43:33.650
So that's a bummer.

00:43:33.650 --> 00:43:36.210
But on the other
hand, it will allow

00:43:36.210 --> 00:43:39.830
us to do the full
stochastic treatment.

00:43:39.830 --> 00:43:42.341
And it's also a nice, to
me, the master equation

00:43:42.341 --> 00:43:43.590
is useful in kind of two ways.

00:43:43.590 --> 00:43:46.610
One is that it's going
to be a tool for us to do

00:43:46.610 --> 00:43:48.110
analytic calculations.

00:43:48.110 --> 00:43:51.010
But it's also kind
of a principled way

00:43:51.010 --> 00:43:53.300
of organizing your thoughts
so that you can go and do

00:43:53.300 --> 00:43:55.860
stochastic simulations, if
that's what you want to do.

00:43:55.860 --> 00:43:58.240
So it's also just kind
of like a weigh station

00:43:58.240 --> 00:44:01.150
to kind of help you
set up your simulation.

00:44:15.754 --> 00:44:17.170
So what we're going
to do is we're

00:44:17.170 --> 00:44:20.260
going to ask about
the general way

00:44:20.260 --> 00:44:23.240
