01:00:42.334 --> 01:00:44.950
equation that would have gotten
you to that master equation.

01:00:44.950 --> 01:00:46.990
So I think just from
the terms you can do it.

01:00:46.990 --> 01:00:49.530
You could also do like
moment generating functions

01:00:49.530 --> 01:00:51.620
to get to how things change.

01:00:51.620 --> 01:00:59.540
But I mean I think that it's
really from this, for example,

01:00:59.540 --> 01:01:04.050
I think it tells you that that
was the differential equation.

01:01:04.050 --> 01:01:06.980
Does that--

01:01:06.980 --> 01:01:10.100
I mean it's sort of--
the way that we typically

01:01:10.100 --> 01:01:12.350
do things these things, is
that we have a differential

01:01:12.350 --> 01:01:14.790
equation, and then we
construct the master equation.

01:01:14.790 --> 01:01:17.248
So then we already knew what
the differential equation was.

01:01:17.248 --> 01:01:20.100
But I think just from the
terms in your master equation,

01:01:20.100 --> 01:01:22.769
you can say, all right.

01:01:22.769 --> 01:01:25.102
This was the differential
equation that it started with.

01:01:31.486 --> 01:01:33.360
Any other questions
about what happened here?

01:01:40.320 --> 01:01:43.650
So we have, I think, a fair
number, a fair knowledge

01:01:43.650 --> 01:01:45.890
of what's going on here now.

01:01:45.890 --> 01:01:49.930
We know that the
equilibrium distribution

01:01:49.930 --> 01:01:52.620
of mRNA in the cell is
going to be Poisson.

01:01:52.620 --> 01:01:54.600
We also know that
the distribution

01:01:54.600 --> 01:01:57.230
of the number of mRNA produced
per sell cycle is also Poisson.

01:01:57.230 --> 01:02:00.600
But it's a different
Poisson from the first one.

01:02:00.600 --> 01:02:04.097
We know that the number of
proteins produced per mRNA

01:02:04.097 --> 01:02:05.805
is going to be
geometrically distributed.

01:02:08.775 --> 01:02:10.400
The one thing that
we have not yet done

01:02:10.400 --> 01:02:17.650
is to ask about the distribution
of protein in the cell.

01:02:17.650 --> 01:02:19.352
So let's say
something about that.

01:02:19.352 --> 01:02:21.060
I'm not going to do
the whole derivation.

01:02:21.060 --> 01:02:22.560
Because it's harder.

01:02:22.560 --> 01:02:27.180
But I encourage you to--
even the continuous version

01:02:27.180 --> 01:02:30.840
of the derivation is
definitely harder than this.

01:02:30.840 --> 01:02:36.620
But then the discrete
derivation is even worse.

01:02:36.620 --> 01:02:38.060
So what we're going
to talk about,

01:02:38.060 --> 01:02:39.530
and the way we'll
typically maybe

01:02:39.530 --> 01:02:41.613
think about this from the
standpoint of this class

01:02:41.613 --> 01:02:46.257
is the continuous
approximation to-- oh,

01:02:46.257 --> 01:02:47.840
that might have ended
up being useful.

01:02:47.840 --> 01:02:49.790
Well it's OK.

01:02:49.790 --> 01:02:54.499
Is the continuous approximation
to the real answer.

01:02:54.499 --> 01:02:56.790
And in particular, just the
way that the exponential is

01:02:56.790 --> 01:03:00.820
the continuous approximation
of the geometric distribution,

01:03:00.820 --> 01:03:04.370
in the same way you can
think about the equilibrium

01:03:04.370 --> 01:03:06.370
distribution of
protein in the cell.

01:03:06.370 --> 01:03:08.720
In this model is going
to be gamma distributed.

01:03:08.720 --> 01:03:11.110
But gamma is a
continuous distribution.

01:03:11.110 --> 01:03:17.880
But it's a continuous analog
of the negative binomial.

01:03:17.880 --> 01:03:33.401
So let me just make sure I'm--
and Sunney Xie actually has

01:03:33.401 --> 01:03:38.670
a nice PRL paper where he
derives the gamma distribution.

01:03:38.670 --> 01:03:40.970
But even earlier
actually Paulson

01:03:40.970 --> 01:03:43.700
had derived this negative
binomial distribution,

01:03:43.700 --> 01:03:45.690
the discrete version
of the solution.

01:03:56.910 --> 01:03:59.379
So this is the number
of protein per cell.

01:03:59.379 --> 01:04:00.420
We already know the mean.

01:04:04.870 --> 01:04:09.410
So this is approximately
distributed as a gamma.

01:04:09.410 --> 01:04:12.410
A gamma is a distribution
that requires two parameters

01:04:12.410 --> 01:04:13.330
to describe.

01:04:13.330 --> 01:04:17.230
So a Poisson can be described
by single parameter.

01:04:17.230 --> 01:04:19.150
Gamma is typically
described by two.

01:04:23.580 --> 01:04:29.806
And b is going to
be the burst size,

01:04:29.806 --> 01:04:43.390
whereas a is the mean number
of bursts per cell cycle, which

01:04:43.390 --> 01:04:45.850
is the same as the
mean number of mRNA

01:04:45.850 --> 01:04:47.500
produced, so mean
number of bursts.

01:04:56.670 --> 01:05:00.080
So the gamma of this a, b.

01:05:18.850 --> 01:05:19.350
All right.

01:05:19.350 --> 01:05:23.920
So the gamma of a is
the gamma function.

01:05:23.920 --> 01:05:29.360
It's equal to-- now is
it a minus 1 factorial?

01:05:29.360 --> 01:05:31.770
I always get the-- is it a
minus 1 or a plus 1 factorial.

01:05:31.770 --> 01:05:33.590
Anybody remember this?

01:05:33.590 --> 01:05:34.370
Yeah, a minus 1.

01:05:43.830 --> 01:05:45.290
I mean it's like
a lot of things.

01:05:45.290 --> 01:05:46.740
You look at this equation.

01:05:46.740 --> 01:05:48.980
It doesn't really
mean a whole lot.

01:05:48.980 --> 01:05:51.540
But I think that a reasonable
way to think about this

01:05:51.540 --> 01:05:55.810
is the gamma is
approximately what

01:05:55.810 --> 01:06:02.260
you get when you add together
a different exponentials

01:06:02.260 --> 01:06:06.515
with length scale, given by b.

01:06:06.515 --> 01:06:08.140
When you add probability
distributions,

01:06:08.140 --> 01:06:09.909
you have to do a convolution.

01:06:09.909 --> 01:06:11.700
So in some ways, the
way to think about it,

01:06:11.700 --> 01:06:12.908
and this kind of makes sense.

01:06:12.908 --> 01:06:15.720
Because what is
happening is that it

01:06:15.720 --> 01:06:18.631
takes something of
order cell division time

01:06:18.631 --> 01:06:19.880
for these proteins to go away.

01:06:19.880 --> 01:06:22.200
Because they're stable.

01:06:22.200 --> 01:06:25.070
Now each-- and so then
what you want to know

01:06:25.070 --> 01:06:27.200
is how many proteins
are kind of produced

01:06:27.200 --> 01:06:30.200
over the course of a cell cycle.

01:06:30.200 --> 01:06:36.144
Well that actually you can get
at by asking how many bursts

01:06:36.144 --> 01:06:37.060
are there going to be.

01:06:37.060 --> 01:06:38.430
And then how big are the bursts?

01:06:41.450 --> 01:06:47.580
So indeed, the mean here
is equal to a times b.

01:06:47.580 --> 01:06:50.860
And the variance is equal
to a times b squared.

01:06:56.551 --> 01:06:58.550
So for example, if you
have a single exponential

01:06:58.550 --> 01:07:06.270
distribution, with burst size
b, then this is what you get.

01:07:06.270 --> 01:07:09.820
So this is the probability
that you get n proteins.

01:07:09.820 --> 01:07:11.500
And this is this function of n.

01:07:11.500 --> 01:07:15.500
So for a single burst, this
is exponentially distributed.

01:07:15.500 --> 01:07:18.990
So this is the
continuous version.

01:07:18.990 --> 01:07:22.830
Now if we add together
multiple of these bursts,

01:07:22.830 --> 01:07:25.330
this is really saying that we
sample from this distribution,

01:07:25.330 --> 01:07:26.240
say twice.

01:07:26.240 --> 01:07:29.120
And then we add the
resulting value.

01:07:29.120 --> 01:07:30.790
So this is a convolution.

01:07:30.790 --> 01:07:32.500
You guys will have
an opportunity

01:07:32.500 --> 01:07:35.310
to practice this on
your problem sets.

01:07:35.310 --> 01:07:36.910
But what happens
is that you end up

01:07:36.910 --> 01:07:39.660
getting something that looks
like-- it's going to go.

01:07:42.920 --> 01:07:44.380
So it increases linearly.

01:07:44.380 --> 01:07:46.470
If you added three
of them together

01:07:46.470 --> 01:07:47.871
this increase is quadratic.

01:07:47.871 --> 01:07:49.120
And it kind of goes like that.

01:07:49.120 --> 01:07:52.415
So this thing
becomes kind of-- it

01:07:52.415 --> 01:07:54.652
goes from a
distribution where it's

01:07:54.652 --> 01:07:57.110
peaked at 0, to something that's
peaked at a nonzero value.

01:08:00.060 --> 01:08:02.660
Now you can ask,
for example, what

01:08:02.660 --> 01:08:09.810
happens as for a large a,
if you have many bursts,

01:08:09.810 --> 01:08:11.330
what does this thing look like?

01:08:11.330 --> 01:08:14.415
Oh, I wish I hadn't erased
my probability distributions.

01:08:17.290 --> 01:08:22.233
So what are the gamma
converged to for large a?

01:08:22.233 --> 01:08:23.149
A normal distribution.

01:08:23.149 --> 01:08:23.950
Right?

01:08:23.950 --> 01:08:26.359
So that's the central
limit theorem.

01:08:26.359 --> 01:08:28.939
If you take any well-behaved
probability distribution,

01:08:28.939 --> 01:08:29.649
you add it.

01:08:29.649 --> 01:08:31.821
You sample from it many times.

01:08:31.821 --> 01:08:33.279
Then you end up
getting a Gaussian.

01:08:38.528 --> 01:08:40.069
If you don't remember
that very well,

01:08:40.069 --> 01:08:43.580
then this is something to
read about over the weekend.

01:08:49.109 --> 01:08:50.580
Just like the
Poisson is also going

01:08:50.580 --> 01:08:57.745
to go to-- for large
lambda, the Poisson

01:08:57.745 --> 01:08:58.870
also looks like a Gaussian.

01:08:58.870 --> 01:09:00.330
Can somebody give
an explanation,

01:09:00.330 --> 01:09:03.500
an intuitive explanation
for why that should be?

01:09:03.500 --> 01:09:06.773
Why it-- yes?

01:09:06.773 --> 01:09:08.697
AUDIENCE: Because in a
Poisson distribution,

01:09:08.697 --> 01:09:10.307
you can't have
anything negative.

01:09:10.307 --> 01:09:10.890
PROFESSOR: OK.

01:09:10.890 --> 01:09:12.848
So a Poisson distribution
can't have anything--

01:09:12.848 --> 01:09:14.970
but now I feel like
you're arguing against me.

01:09:14.970 --> 01:09:17.579
Because a Gaussian has
negative values, right?

01:09:17.579 --> 01:09:18.245
AUDIENCE: Right.

01:09:18.245 --> 01:09:22.946
So when the mean is really
small, only have [INAUDIBLE].

01:09:22.946 --> 01:09:23.529
PROFESSOR: OK.

01:09:23.529 --> 01:09:24.100
Yeah.

01:09:24.100 --> 01:09:24.990
All right.

01:09:24.990 --> 01:09:28.755
So what you're saying is
that Poisson for small lambda

01:09:28.755 --> 01:09:30.035
it can't go negative.

01:09:32.221 --> 01:09:32.720
OK.

01:09:32.720 --> 01:09:35.568
No I think that that's true.

01:09:35.568 --> 01:09:37.609
Yeah, and so somehow the
probability distribution

01:09:37.609 --> 01:09:39.974
is somehow piling
up, as you say.

01:09:39.974 --> 01:09:41.974
What are some other ways
of thinking about this?

01:09:50.463 --> 01:09:51.379
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:10:00.289 --> 01:10:04.744
Because if you have a low lambda
that means it's a Poisson.

01:10:04.744 --> 01:10:08.704
And then I'm just
imagining stretching out.

01:10:08.704 --> 01:10:09.240
[INAUDIBLE]

01:10:12.137 --> 01:10:12.720
PROFESSOR: OK.

01:10:12.720 --> 01:10:14.051
So I think that's fair.

01:10:14.051 --> 01:10:15.550
Another way we can
think about this,

01:10:15.550 --> 01:10:17.425
is let's say that we
have some process that's

01:10:17.425 --> 01:10:20.600
occurring randomly over
some period of time.

01:10:20.600 --> 01:10:23.470
And this could be
say, mRNA production.

01:10:23.470 --> 01:10:26.250
And here this is just the
number that we observe here,

01:10:26.250 --> 01:10:29.580
this is going to be a Poisson,
with some mean lambda.

01:10:29.580 --> 01:10:33.580
Now let's just say that I take
another one, same process,

01:10:33.580 --> 01:10:34.520
same period of time.

01:10:34.520 --> 01:10:36.186
How is this guy going
to be distributed?

01:10:38.229 --> 01:10:39.520
So this also Poisson of lambda.

01:10:43.430 --> 01:10:47.740
Now let's say I take this
probability distribution,

01:10:47.740 --> 01:10:49.970
and I take this
probability distribution.

01:10:49.970 --> 01:10:52.259
And I convolve them.

01:10:52.259 --> 01:10:54.050
I'm going to do the
calculation of my head.

01:10:54.050 --> 01:10:57.100
I did it.

01:10:57.100 --> 01:11:02.410
So for those of you who haven't
done convolutions-- whatever.

01:11:02.410 --> 01:11:04.380
Yes, what's the new
distribution going to be?

01:11:11.380 --> 01:11:13.242
Poisson 2 lambda.

01:11:13.242 --> 01:11:14.450
And why does that have to be?

01:11:16.306 --> 01:11:18.306
AUDIENCE: That line was
sort of you put it by n.

01:11:21.690 --> 01:11:22.370
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:11:22.370 --> 01:11:22.911
That's right.

01:11:22.911 --> 01:11:25.100
This line, I just kind of
like I just made it up.

01:11:25.100 --> 01:11:25.990
I could have just said, oh.

01:11:25.990 --> 01:11:27.948
Well it's the same process
occurring over here.

01:11:27.948 --> 01:11:29.247
So we have to have the mean.

01:11:29.247 --> 01:11:31.080
It's still is going to
be a Poisson process.

01:11:31.080 --> 01:11:35.085
And the mean has to
be the-- well we just

01:11:35.085 --> 01:11:35.960
had twice the length.

01:11:35.960 --> 01:11:38.210
And indeed, for independent
probability distributions,

01:11:38.210 --> 01:11:39.655
means always add.

01:11:39.655 --> 01:11:41.780
So this all consistent will
all the things we know.

01:11:41.780 --> 01:11:43.690
So this has to be a
Poisson of 2 lambda.

01:11:43.690 --> 01:11:45.370
If I add another
segment on here,

01:11:45.370 --> 01:11:47.600
it has to Poisson of 3 lambda.

01:11:47.600 --> 01:11:51.590
But what you see is that we see
that Poisson of n lambda, which

01:11:51.590 --> 01:11:52.840
is the sum over many Poissons.

01:11:55.724 --> 01:11:57.890
Poissons are well-behaved
probability distributions.

01:11:57.890 --> 01:11:58.560
You add them
together, you're going

01:11:58.560 --> 01:11:59.990
to have to get a Gaussian.

01:11:59.990 --> 01:12:02.840
So you can see that the
Poisson has to become

01:12:02.840 --> 01:12:03.940
Gaussian for large lambda.

01:12:03.940 --> 01:12:05.010
And indeed it does.

01:12:09.520 --> 01:12:11.660
So there's a comment
about this in the--

01:12:11.660 --> 01:12:13.950
AUDIENCE: It's a little bit
more complicated than this

01:12:13.950 --> 01:12:16.990
because obviously you
always just divide

01:12:16.990 --> 01:12:18.430
from lambda [INAUDIBLE].

01:12:21.895 --> 01:12:24.617
Like you would have to say
that Poisson lambda is just

01:12:24.617 --> 01:12:28.340
like a combination of S--

01:12:28.340 --> 01:12:29.410
PROFESSOR: OK.

01:12:29.410 --> 01:12:31.860
You're saying that if I do
this calculation backwards,

01:12:31.860 --> 01:12:32.710
I'm going to get into trouble.

01:12:32.710 --> 01:12:34.043
Because if I try to break them--

01:12:34.043 --> 01:12:36.689
AUDIENCE: So if you
require lambda to be-- you

01:12:36.689 --> 01:12:39.736
have to have like a significant
probability of getting at least

01:12:39.736 --> 01:12:40.970
one candidate, right?

01:12:40.970 --> 01:12:45.670
PROFESSOR: So I'd say lambda has
to be much, much larger than 1.

01:12:45.670 --> 01:12:50.986
So once you're at lambda of
100, it looks like a Gaussian.

01:12:50.986 --> 01:12:53.110
And in Sunney's paper, he
had a comment about this.

01:12:53.110 --> 01:12:54.526
Does anybody
remember what it was?

01:12:59.160 --> 01:13:01.290
Was mRNA production
really well described

01:13:01.290 --> 01:13:06.395
as-- they mention
that actually there

01:13:06.395 --> 01:13:12.105
is some violation of
this model in the data.

01:13:12.105 --> 01:13:14.079
AUDIENCE: Does it
go into eukaryotes?

01:13:14.079 --> 01:13:16.120
PROFESSOR: Oh, as soon as
you go into eukaryotes,

01:13:16.120 --> 01:13:18.160
this is why I stay
away from them.

01:13:18.160 --> 01:13:21.350
But even in their
data, in E. coli,

01:13:21.350 --> 01:13:23.080
they actually
observed a deviation.

01:13:29.955 --> 01:13:32.500
So what they found is that there
was a cell cycle dependence

01:13:32.500 --> 01:13:36.810
to this bursting rate,
i.e. the mRNA production

01:13:36.810 --> 01:13:39.510
over the course
of the cell cycle.

01:13:39.510 --> 01:13:41.450
And presumably their
conclusion of this

01:13:41.450 --> 01:13:43.740
was that you have this guy.

01:13:43.740 --> 01:13:47.160
And then he turns
into, gets longer.

01:13:47.160 --> 01:13:50.817
And then eventually he septates,
and then you get two cells.

01:13:55.540 --> 01:13:59.940
What he found is that these
longer cells had actually

01:13:59.940 --> 01:14:03.210
a larger rate of mRNA synthesis
than the smaller cells.

01:14:03.210 --> 01:14:04.460
And actually this makes sense.

01:14:04.460 --> 01:14:07.590
Because here you maybe have
just one copy of the genome.

01:14:07.590 --> 01:14:12.930
Whereas here you might have--
you're making a second copy.

01:14:12.930 --> 01:14:16.180
So you might have two
copies of that gene.

01:14:16.180 --> 01:14:21.117
So it may make sense that this
bursting rate should grow.

01:14:21.117 --> 01:14:22.700
But does that mean
that you should not

01:14:22.700 --> 01:14:26.130
expect it to be a Poisson
distribution for the number

01:14:26.130 --> 01:14:27.642
of bursts per cell cycle?

01:14:33.540 --> 01:14:34.040
No.

01:14:34.040 --> 01:14:37.420
It actually is still-- it still
is described by a Poisson.

01:14:37.420 --> 01:14:40.650
Because you can just say,
this is the cell cycle.

01:14:40.650 --> 01:14:43.480
And here this is
Poisson of sum lambda 1.

01:14:43.480 --> 01:14:45.270
Here is a Poisson
of sum lambda 2.

01:14:45.270 --> 01:14:46.970
So there could be
a different rate

01:14:46.970 --> 01:14:47.700
over the course of the thing.

01:14:47.700 --> 01:14:49.241
But you still have
just two Poissons.

01:14:49.241 --> 01:14:51.230
You still get another Poisson.

01:14:51.230 --> 01:14:54.215
So adding Poissons,
gives you backup Poisson.

01:14:54.215 --> 01:14:56.090
They don't have to have
the same mean lambda.

01:15:04.230 --> 01:15:07.550
I just want to make
one comment about what

01:15:07.550 --> 01:15:09.940
you have to do once you start
thinking about eukaryotes.

01:15:09.940 --> 01:15:15.540
And the basic-- so you can
see the gamma distribution

01:15:15.540 --> 01:15:19.877
can either be peaked at 0, or it
can be peaked at nonzero value.

01:15:19.877 --> 01:15:21.710
So most, for like highly
expressed proteins,

01:15:21.710 --> 01:15:24.880
you'll see that it looks
something like this.

01:15:24.880 --> 01:15:27.620
Now for eukaryotes,
you also have

01:15:27.620 --> 01:15:30.490
to consider there's
some rate that you

01:15:30.490 --> 01:15:33.500
go between an active
and inactive promoter.

01:15:37.790 --> 01:15:40.470
And this actually makes
things much more complicated.

01:15:40.470 --> 01:15:43.220
So there's a rate
going to inactive,

01:15:43.220 --> 01:15:45.990
a rate going to active.

01:15:45.990 --> 01:15:48.390
And so now if you
look at, for example,

01:15:48.390 --> 01:15:50.980
the mRNA number per
cell, you'll see

01:15:50.980 --> 01:15:53.950
that it is no longer a Poisson.

01:15:53.950 --> 01:15:57.230
And I encourage you, if you're
curious about such things,

01:15:57.230 --> 01:16:00.340
to come up and look at this.

01:16:00.340 --> 01:16:02.320
The solution for the
steady state distribution

01:16:02.320 --> 01:16:03.528
has been solved analytically.

01:16:03.528 --> 01:16:06.630
For example, Arjun Raj, who
is the author of the review

01:16:06.630 --> 01:16:11.100
that you guys just read,
